default3. defaultThe case for financial transparency and accountabdefaultility - tdefaulthe UK as a centre of excellence for best practice in corporate Governance.default&#xa0;default3.1.default defaultAt the G8 Leaders Summit in June the Prime Minister recognised the need for increased transparency and accountably for extractives companies stating that 
default“
default… oil, gas 
defaultand mining companies should report what they pay to governments, and that governments should publish what they receive, so that natural resources are a blessing and not a curse.”
default 
defaultThere are several tools that the UK, both unilaterally, and as part of inter
defaultnational coalitions, should seek to use to ensure that UK extractive industries are part of the solution to creating thriving, sustainable societies wherever they operate, and not part of the problem.
default 
defaultThe key areas where UK regulation can support developin
defaultg countries are through transparency and accountability.  
default&#xa0;
default3.2default 
defaultThe UK, through support for the EU Accounting and Transparency Directives, has played a key role in new laws that will increase the transparency of payments made by extractive industries to go
defaultvernments in every country.  This will help citizens in many countries hold their governments to account and begin to tackle some of the problems of corruption in and around extractives projects and developments.  
default&#xa0;
default3.3default 
defaultThis does not go far enough however.
default  Without further information beyond details of payments, it is impossible to place the information on payments in context and go beyond the simple question of what governments are doing with the money they receive, to being able to hold both governments a
defaultnd companies accountable for the terms under which 
defaultsuch 
defaultrevenues are received, to ensure they are both correct and a good deal for citizens. 
defaultIt is increasingly accepted that 
defaultone sided
default contracts
default,
default invariably favouring extractives companies, sharp practices s
defaultuch as transfer mispricing and the use of tax havens, notably Switzerland in commodity trading, are causing developing countries to lose out on the benefits of the resource boom of the last 20 years
default.
default 
default&#xa0;defaultCountry by Country Reporting 
default&#xa0;
default3.4default 
defaultThat greater 
defaulttransparency is part of the solution is also increasingly accepted.  The International Development Committee and the European Parliament have both endorsed 
defaultthe need for full, public, country by country reporting by multinational companies
default.
default  The G8 in Loug
defaulth Erne also committed to developing a form 
defaultof country by country reporting,
default however the G8 did not recommend this information be placed in the public domain
default.
default There is a clear need for this information to be made public
default. C
defaultountry by country reporting will e
defaultnable citizens to be able to see the full picture of what extractive industries are contributing (or not) to their societies and be able to demand accountability either from governments for poor contract negotiation, or companies for sharp practice.  
default&#xa0;
default3.5default 
defaultWhile the G8 has accepted that governments around the world will benefit from country by country reporting, without making such reporting public there does not appear to be any mechanism to ensure that all governments would be able to access such informat
defaultion, without either every country making a legislative change to require such information, or through a substantial revision to existing bilateral and multilateral information exchange agreements.  In light of the fact that the G8 has committed to requirin
defaultg companies to providing country by country reporting, the additional costs of making such reporting public will be minimal. This could result in a win-win for both business and society, and companies could point to this practice to enhance their reputatio
defaultn. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBeneficial Ownership Transparency 
default&#xa0;
default3.6default Alongside country-
defaultby
default-
defaultcountry reporting there is also a need for increased transparency of those who really own extractive industry companies.  As highlighted by both the G8 and the Africa Progress Panel the lack of public transparency over who owns extractive industry companie
defaults is a serious problem.  In the Democratic Republic of Congo 
default(DRC) 
defaultfive mining contracts were awarded to anonymous companies in the British Virgin Islands 
default(BVI) 
defaultat a vastly under market rate and then sold on at market rate to major extractives companies, i
defaultncluding some listed on UK exchanges; the estimated cost to the DRC was $1.35bn or twice the health and education budget.  The 
defaultidentities
default of those who owned, and benefitted from the BVI based company remain unknown
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.default8default 
defaultPublic registries of the real, beneficial owners would address this problem and not only provide a way to identify those profiting and hold them to account, but also to deter such practices form ever happening.  The UK made improving 
defaultinformation about 
defaultcomp
defaultany ownership a key part of the G8, with the Prime Minister making it clear he publicly supports public registries
default,
default which
default the Department of Business Innovation and Skills 
defaultis now consulting on.  At the Open for Growth summit in London before the G8 some ex
defaulttractive industries also supported public registries
default, this has since been followed by
default t
defaulthe Institute of Directors, the 
defaulthead of the 
defaultBritish Banking Association
default, the 
defaulthead of tax for the 
defaultConfederation of British Industry
default and the World Economic Forum
default Council on Organized Crime, all of whom
default 
defaulthave come on in support of pu
defaultblic registries
default, as well as Rio Tinto and the International Council on Mining and Meta
defaultls
default.
default 
defaultPublic registries could confer clear benefits on the extractives industry, 
defaultparticularly in the c
defaultase of joint ventures where it is becoming increasingly easy for companies to identify who is behind prospective partners.
default&#xa0;
