defaultThere mu
defaultst be a consistent approach across government on business and human rights in relation to the extractives sector
default.
default In particular, UK Trade &amp; Investment 
defaultmust be transparent about its promotion of potential extractive projects and should not promote projects
default which pose risks to human rights, where it is not clear how the company concerned proposes to mitigate those risks. 
default4.default5default 
defaultFinally
default,
default we urge the UK government to support and encourage the passage of the new European regulation in two key areas which will imp
defaultrove corporate transparency and accountability. The first is the Non-Financial Reporting for companies on their supply chains and human rights
default,
default and the second is for companies and individuals using natural resources
default to conduct risk-based supply chain due 
defaultdiligence that meets international standards endorsed
default by the United Nations
default and by the OECD. The aim of such legislation would be to ensure that European companies source commodities responsibly and avoid funding conflict and instability or contributing to
default the commission of grave human rights abuses through their purchases. 
